'\" t
.TH "vTTY-SeatManager" "8" "" "vtty-seatmanager"
.\" -----------------------------------------------------------------
.\" -----------------------------------------------------------------
.SH "NAME"
vtty-seatmanager - vTTY 'display' manager
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.B vtty-seatmanager
is a service that runs in place of a display manager to start one
or more vTTY instances on each graphical capable seat.
.SH "STARTUP AND USAGE"
.B vtty-seatmanager
can be set to start at boot, by enabling the
.B vtty-seatmanager.service
where it will then be linked as the
.B display-manager.service
.PP
Upon startup, a default vtty instance is started on all available
seats. If a user logs into the getty, the vtty instance is seen as
in-use. Once in use, if a second instance is needed (similar to
switching to tty2, or tty3, etc) pressing the
.B SecureAttentionKey
for
.BR systemd-logind(1),
which is usually
.B Ctrl+Alt+Shift+Esc,
causes a second instance to be started on the seat.
.PP
If the user's session on the first instance is logged off, pressing
the
.B SecureAttentionKey
sequence again will switch to the first instance, allowing a user to
login.
.PP
If both instances are still in use, and the
.B SecureAttentionKey
sequence is pressed again, it starts a 3rd instance with a getty.
.PP
.B vtty-seatmanager
queries logind's
.B NAutoVTs
attribute for the maximum number of sessions to create. This can be set
in
.BR logind.conf(5)
.RS 4
Note that
.B vtty-seatmanager
does not parse the logind config file directly, but uses logind's dbus
interface to get this value.
.RE
.RS 4
Note that logind's default value for this option is typically 6.
.RE
.PP
If the maximum number of instances have been created, and all are in
use,
.B vtty-seatmanager
will then cycle through all the instances when the
.B SecureAttentionKey
sequence is pressed.
.SH "CONFIGURATION"
.B vtty-seatmanager
has no config files of its own. The only configurable option is the
maximum number of vTTY instances that it will create on a seat, with
the
.B NAutoVTs
option in \fBlogind\fR. See the 
.B NAutoVTs
option in
.BR logind.conf(5)
and note that
.B vtty-seatmanager
does not parse the config file itself, but queries through dbus, so
a daemon reload of
.B logind
may be needed for changes to take effect, as well as a restart of the
.B vtty-seatmanager.
.PP
It is recommended to keep this value at 12 or fewer, as most keyboards
max out at
.B Ctrl+Alt+F12
for session switching.
.SH See Also:
.BR vtty (7)
